# Project: Sawe

Sawe is a personal fork of [Zed](https://github.com/zed-industries/zed) maintained by Simonov Pavel ([@Sipaha](https://github.com/Sipaha)). Repo: <https://github.com/Sipaha/sawe>.

## Entry points

- **Doc bookshelf:** [`docs/INDEX.md`](docs/INDEX.md) — start here every session after this file.
- **Supervisor workflow** (multi-agent dispatch, plan docs, verification ritual): [`docs/workflow/supervisor-mode.md`](docs/workflow/supervisor-mode.md).
- **Where do I write this?** → [`docs/workflow/doc-discipline.md`](docs/workflow/doc-discipline.md).
- **What's different from upstream Zed?** → [`FORK.md`](FORK.md).

## Resume protocol — "ты автономный супервизор. Продолжай работу"

When the user says any of these (any language, any phrasing close to
"continue work as the autonomous supervisor"):

- `ты автономный супервизор`
- `продолжай работу` / `продолжай`
- `autonomous supervisor` / `continue work` / `continue`
- `resume`

…the supervisor **immediately** does this — no clarifying questions:

1. `Glob` `docs/findings/*-session-handoff.md` → `Read` the
   lexicographically-latest one. That file is the previous session's
   pause snapshot — it lists the outstanding task pool, open
   architectural decisions, and active gotchas.
2. `Read` `docs/workflow/supervisor-mode.md` § 7 "NEXT" — the priority
   heuristic for picking the next phase.
3. `git log --oneline -15` — sanity-check the recent commit chain
   matches what the handoff doc claims.
4. **Pick the next phase** from the pool per § 7 heuristic (no
   priority polling — `feedback_supervisor_no_priority_questions.md`
   in memory) and start the work in the **same turn**:
   - HEAVY → write plan-doc inline-friendly + commit + dispatch a
     sub-agent in a worktree.
   - LIGHT → just do it.

If there is **no handoff finding** (first-ever session, or someone
purged them): read `docs/INDEX.md` first, then start a sensible LIGHT
or HEAVY pick based on what's at the top of the plans table.

When the supervisor pauses a session (user says "сделай паузу",
"приостанови", "пауза", "stop", "context reset"), it **must write a
fresh `docs/findings/YYYY-MM-DD-session-handoff.md`** capturing:
commit chain since the last handoff, what shipped, outstanding pool,
open architectural decisions, active gotchas. Then update
`docs/INDEX.md` § findings to add the new row at the top. This is what
makes the next resume bootstrap-free.

## Fork philosophy — read this before suggesting changes

Sawe is a standalone product. We do **not** merge or cherry-pick from
upstream Zed. The codebase is fully ours — every crate is fair game for
bug fixes, refactors, renames, cleanup, and feature work driven by product
needs, not by upstream-diff hygiene. There is no "untouched core" zone:
if `editor`, `language`, `lsp`, `multi_buffer`, `project`, `terminal`,
`dap`, `vim`, `theme`, `gpui`, etc. need changes to make a feature work
right, change them.

Rules that still apply:

- **Disable, don't delete** for explicitly-disabled upstream subsystems
  (collab, auto_update, telemetry, Zeta, native cloud LLM, Sentry uploads,
  upstream agent panel). Keep the crates in the workspace and the code in
  tree — only init / dispatch / UI registration sites are commented out
  (`if false { … }` is fine). Re-enabling is a one-line change, and we
  haven't audited what other crates implicitly depend on these
  subsystems' types, traits, or globals.

- **Locked rebrand identifiers** (spec §3, change requires user approval):
  display name `Sawe` (Dock/About/title bar); CLI binary
  `sawe`; macOS bundle ids `ru.sipaha.sawe[-{preview,nightly,dev,debug}]`;
  URL scheme `sawe://`; config dir `~/.config/sawe/` (Linux),
  `~/Library/Application Support/Sawe/` (macOS — no space in path,
  display name keeps space), `%APPDATA%\Sawe\` (Windows — no space in
  path); GitHub `Sipaha/sawe`; attribution string `Fork of Zed by
  Zed Industries, Inc., modified by Simonov Pavel`; per-project config
  dir `.sawe/` (replacing upstream `.zed/`; `.zed_server` /
  `.zed_wsl_server` remain unchanged as preserved upstream identifiers).
  These are user-visible identity, not merge-friendliness — they don't
  change just because the merge cost went away.

- **License compliance**: never modify `LICENSE-{GPL,AGPL,APACHE}` or
  remove `Copyright Zed Industries, Inc.` lines. Fork contents under same
  SPDX as upstream (`GPL-3.0-or-later` editor, `AGPL-3.0` collab,
  `Apache-2.0` libraries). Inherited Zed legal docs live in
  `legal/upstream-zed/` and don't apply to this fork's binaries (no
  service infrastructure).

## What's disabled (do NOT try to "fix" these without explicit instruction)

| Subsystem | Where disabled |
|---|---|
| `auto_update` | init skipped in `crates/zed/src/main.rs`; "Check for Updates" menu hidden in `app_menus.rs` |
| `telemetry` | `send_event` + `flush_events_inner` early-return; defaults `metrics:false`/`diagnostics:false` |
| `collab` / `collab_ui` | `collab_ui::init` skipped; CollabPanel not loaded; "Collab Panel" menu hidden |
| Sign-in | title-bar `render_sign_in_button` not invoked; onboarding `SignIn` action no-op'd |
| Native cloud LLM | `CloudLanguageModelProvider::new` wrapped in `if false`; "Zed Agent" entry hidden in agent panel |
| `zeta` (edit prediction) | `EditPredictionProvider::Zed` arm returns `None`; default `provider:"none"` |
| Sentry uploads | `upload_panic`/`upload_minidump`/`upload_build_timings` all early-return; local panic logs preserved |
| CI workflows | 41 workflows hard-disabled (`if: false`); `run_tests.yml` is `workflow_dispatch:` only |
| `agent_ui::AgentPanel` dock + Welcome agent card | `initialize_agent_panel` not called from `crates/zed/src/zed.rs::initialize_panels`; `crates/workspace/src/welcome.rs::render_agent_card` gated off via `false &&`. `agent_ui::init` still runs (inline_assistant / rules_library / context_server modal depend on it) — only the user-facing panel surface is hidden. Fork uses `solution_agent` for AI. |

## What's kept

- **Extension registry on `zed.dev`** — extensions panel still browses / installs from upstream registry.
- **External agents via ACP** (Claude Code subprocess, Gemini CLI, etc.) — `agent_servers` + `acp*` are wired up; the upstream `AgentPanel` UI surface is hidden in this fork. AI in this fork = `claude` subprocess driven by `solution_agent`, NOT API tokens.
- **BYOK providers** (Copilot, Anthropic via API key, Ollama, etc.) — defined but not promoted in UI.
- **Multi-project Solutions** (`solutions` + `solutions_ui`) — group N catalog projects into one window. See `FORK.md`.
- **Solution-scoped AI sessions** (`solution_agent`) — N parallel Claude Code sessions per Solution, multiplexed onto a shared subprocess per `(solution, agent)` pair. Auth via subscription, not API key. See `FORK.md`.

## Build + test conventions

- Bundling produces `bin/sawe` + `libexec/sawe-bin` (Linux), `Sawe.app/Contents/MacOS/sawe` (macOS — display name stays `Sawe` via plutil override in `script/bundle-mac`), `SaweSetup-*.exe` (Windows).
- Cargo target binary is `target/release/sawe`. The cargo crate name `zed` itself is unchanged: the rename would touch hundreds of files for ~zero functional gain, and any future cherry-pick from upstream into the editor crate would textually conflict on every renamed identifier. Only the `[[bin]] name` is overridden.
- Codesign / notarize gated behind `SAWE_SIGN` env var; default produces unsigned bundles.
- Specs and plans for the rebrand work live in `docs/superpowers/{specs,plans}/`.
- **Build profile depends on who tests next.**
  - *Autonomous / agent-only verification* (cargo test, headless e2e, MCP-socket probes the agent drives itself) → **debug only**: `script/run-mcp --debug`, `cargo build` without `--release`, `cargo test` without `--release`. Don't burn a 3–9 min release compile for an agent's own checks.
  - *Hand-off back to the user for hands-on testing* (they'll actually launch / use the editor and judge the change) → **build `release-fast` proactively**: `cargo build --bin sawe --profile release-fast` (~5 min, run in background). The user's running editor is the release-fast binary at `target/release-fast/sawe` talking to `~/.spk/sawe/config/mcp.sock` (NOT `-dev`); a debug bundle won't replace it, so without this step the "ready to test" hand-off is false. This is required, not optional — the constraint is "no surprise release compiles for agent-only work," not "never compile release."
  - Full `cargo build --release` and `script/bundle-*` remain reserved for the maintainer.
- **`script/run-mcp` only compiles the binary if it's _missing_** (`if [[ ! -x "$binary" ]]`). After editing any crate, run `cargo build --bin sawe` yourself first — otherwise `run-mcp` happily launches the stale binary and you'll silently test old code (a binary with a stale mtime / no expected `strings` match is the tell). No special feature flags are needed; `workspace.screenshot` works in plain debug builds under the native `--headless` platform (see "Screenshots" below).
- **`cargo build … | tail` masks cargo's exit code** — the pipe reports `tail`'s status (always 0), so a failed build looks like it "succeeded" (and leaves the old binary in place). Use `set -o pipefail`, or don't pipe and grep the captured output for `^error` / `could not compile`.
- **The rust-analyzer flycheck (`cargo check --workspace --all-targets`) holds `target/debug/.cargo-lock`.** If your `cargo build`/`cargo check` sits on "Blocking waiting for file lock on build directory" for minutes, `pkill -f "cargo check --workspace"` (it restarts harmlessly when RA next needs it).
- **`pkill`/`kill` with a pattern that matches `sawe` can match the issuing Bash shell itself** → the command reports exit 144. That's noise; the kill still happened. Prefer `kill <pid>` by PID, or run the kill in a separate command from the one that depends on its result.
- **`--features test-support` is usable as a superset but hard-codes `util::paths::home_dir()` to `/home/zed`** (deterministic test snapshots), so a `test-support` binary won't create its config dirs unless `SAWE_HOME` is set — `script/run-mcp` sets it. You generally don't need `test-support` anymore (the screenshot tool no longer requires it).

## Autonomous testing via embedded MCP

A running `sawe` instance exposes an MCP server over a Unix socket so an agent can drive a real editor for end-to-end testing without a human in the loop. Use this whenever a change touches workspace/project/buffer/LSP behavior and you want to verify it against a live UI rather than only unit tests.

**Extend the MCP surface when it's missing a primitive — don't push the gap onto the operator.** The whole point of this layer is to let an agent verify its own work hands-off. If a check is blocked only because the MCP catalog lacks a tool (a missing input primitive, an unqueryable bit of state, an event you can't subscribe to), the default is to *add that tool* in the same session — mirror the nearest existing tool (registration in the owning domain crate's `init`, a `…Params`/`…Result` pair, a unit test, a bump of the catalog count here), then use it. New primitives are cheap and compound; a human clicking through a manual repro every time does not. Only fall back to asking the operator when the gap is genuinely outside the editor (real GPU display stacking, OS dialogs, external auth). Example: `windows.hover_at` / `windows.hover_id` were added exactly this way to surface `visible_on_hover` UI (timestamps, copy buttons) that a static screenshot can't reveal.

**Socket:** `~/.spk/sawe-dev/config/mcp.sock` for a `--debug` build, `~/.spk/sawe/config/mcp.sock` for release (NOT `~/.config/sawe/` — see `crates/paths`). Single-instance — one editor process at a time holds the socket; a second `sawe` invocation hands off CLI args via the existing socket and exits. Lock file is `…/config/mcp.lock`. (`script/run-mcp` prints the resolved socket path on launch.)

**Tool catalog** (84 tools, JSON-RPC 2.0 over the socket — namespaces: `editor.*`, `windows.*`, `solutions.*`, `solution.git.*`, `catalog.*`, `solution_agent.*`, `workspace.*`, `project.*`, `diagnostics.*`):
- **Probe / control:** `editor.capabilities`, `editor.handle_cli_args`, `editor.{subscribe,unsubscribe,list_subscriptions}`, `editor.{get_operation,cancel_operation}`
- **Solutions / catalog (the multi-project workspace abstraction):** `solutions.{list,get,create,rename,delete,open,close,find_for_path,add_member,add_empty_member,remove_member,reorder_members}`, `catalog.{list,add_project,remove_project,edit_project,refresh_cache,clear_cache}`
- **Solution-wide git (S-SOL-LOG / S-SOL-DSH):** `solution.git.{aggregated_log,status_dashboard,batch_fetch,batch_pull,checkout_pattern}` (the `commit_all` tool + solution-wide commit were removed — commit is per active project)
- **Solution-scoped AI sessions:** `solution_agent.{list_sessions,get_session,create_session,send_message,cancel_turn,close_session,rename_session,restart_agent,authorize_tool_call,reset_context}`
- **Windows:** `windows.{list,focus,close,dispatch_action,send_keystroke,send_text,click_at,click_id,hover_at,hover_id,dump_visual_structure}`
- **Workspace state:** `workspace.{list_buffers,get_effective_settings,dispatch_action,screenshot,dump_visual_structure}` — the two `dump_visual_structure` variants now also return a `clickables: Vec<Clickable>` array; pair with `windows.click_id` to click by stable hash id rather than computing window-relative coordinates yourself.
- **Project / buffer ops:** `project.{list_files,read_buffer,apply_edit,save_buffer,open_file,close_buffer,create_file,delete_file,rename_file,find_in_buffers,goto_definition,find_references}`
- **Diagnostics:** `diagnostics.get` (per-file summaries + per-diagnostic items with severity / message / source / code)

**Self-test recipe:**
1. Build + launch via `script/run-mcp --debug --headless` (debug is mandatory for agent-driven runs — see "Build + test conventions"; `script/run-mcp` builds the binary if missing and prints the socket path when ready). **Always prefer `--headless` for agent work:** it uses the native HeadlessClient + offscreen WgpuHeadlessRenderer (ADR-0002), needs no X server, AND fully supports `workspace.screenshot`. With `$DISPLAY` set the default flips to display mode (real X window); `--display` forces that, `--headless` forces native headless. **Do not try `xvfb-run --display` as a no-display workaround for screenshots — the NVIDIA adapter under Xvfb produces blank PNGs (`docs/findings/2026-05-headless-screenshot-blank.md`).** The dev profile builds in 1-2 min (incremental) and is fine for probing structure / opening Welcome / verifying UI changes. If a check genuinely needs release-profile behaviour, pause and ask the user.
2. Connect via `socat - UNIX-CONNECT:$HOME/.spk/sawe-dev/config/mcp.sock` for ad-hoc probes, or write a small Rust/Python client. JSON-RPC frames are newline-delimited.
3. Always start with `editor.capabilities` to confirm protocol version and supported event kinds.
4. For long-running ops (`solutions.add_member`, `catalog.refresh_cache`) use the returned `operation_id` with `editor.get_operation` to poll, or subscribe via `editor.subscribe { kinds: ["operation_completed", "operation_progress"] }` for push notifications.
5. For visual assertions, `workspace.screenshot {solution_id, format}` returns a real PNG/WebP/JPEG of the editor *window content* (offscreen-rendered — see "Screenshots" below): immune to other windows covering the editor, **works under the native `--headless` mode** (preferred for agents) without needing any X server. `workspace.dump_visual_structure` is still useful as a cheap structured tree but does *not* recurse into rendered pane-item content (`Pane { children: [] }` is ambiguous), so screenshot when you need to see what's actually painted. **If your change touches UI — panel, dock, status row, strip, modal, widget — a screenshot of the running editor is part of "done."** Drive the right panel into view before snapping (`windows.dispatch_action {action_name: "console_panel::ToggleFocus"}` etc.) — `windows.focus` alone doesn't change which dock is visible.
6. **Programmatic UI driving:** trigger keybindings via `windows.send_keystroke` (e.g. `{"window_id":..., "keystroke":"ctrl-shift-p"}`), type plain text via `windows.send_text`, click at coordinates via `windows.click_at` (logical pixels, top-left origin, window-relative — so it works even when the window is partly off-screen; `button: "right"` for context menus), and rest the synthetic cursor over a point/clickable via `windows.hover_at {x,y}` / `windows.hover_id {id}` (a `MouseMove` with no press — reveals `visible_on_hover` affordances like message-bubble timestamps and copy buttons; follow it with `workspace.screenshot`, which repaints and recomputes the hover hit-test from the rested cursor). Most clickable UI in this fork dispatches a named action — prefer `windows.dispatch_action` when one exists since it doesn't depend on rendered geometry. **Caveat:** `ContextMenu` submenus open on *hover*; `windows.click_at` on a submenu item just dismisses the menu. `windows.hover_at`/`hover_id` can now open a submenu by resting on its parent row, but the keyboard path (`down`/`up` to navigate, `right`/`enter` to open a submenu, `enter` to invoke) is still the more deterministic way to exercise a submenu entry. **Notification frames** (`editor/notification`) interleave with responses on the same socket; clients must filter by JSON-RPC `id` and skip frames without one (or with non-matching id) — see `crates/editor_mcp/tests/solutions_add_member_e2e_test.rs::call_tool` for a 10-line implementation.

**Event subscriptions** broadcast as JSON-RPC `editor/notification` frames. Wired kinds: `operation_progress`, `operation_completed`, `solution_changed`, `solution_active_changed`, `solution_member_add_progress`, `solution_member_add_completed`, `solution_active_member_changed`, `buffer_opened`, `buffer_closed`, `buffer_saved`, `buffer_dirty_changed`, `diagnostic_updated`, `lsp_started`, `lsp_stopped`, `window_focused`, `agent_session_created`, `agent_session_closed`, `agent_session_state_changed`, `agent_session_title_changed`, `agent_session_message_appended`, `agent_session_notification_sent`. Deferred: `selection_changed` (Editor-level, not Buffer), `cli_args_received`, `server_shutting_down`. Note: AI session events use the `agent_session_*` prefix (not bare `session_*`) — defensive namespacing against future collisions.

**Integration tests** in `crates/editor_mcp/tests/*_e2e_test.rs` are isolated via `editor_mcp::set_runtime_dir_for_test(tempdir)` — each test pins its own `mcp.{lock,sock}` to a tempdir, so they can run safely alongside a live `sawe` instance and never touch `~/.config/sawe/`. When you write a new e2e test that calls `editor_mcp::start_server`, you MUST call `set_runtime_dir_for_test` first or you will collide with (and corrupt) the user's real lock and socket.

**Screenshots — the agent's "look at the editor" capability:** `workspace.screenshot` returns a real PNG/WebP/JPEG of the editor window content via `gpui_wgpu::WgpuHeadlessRenderer::render_to_image` (renders the current scene into an offscreen texture, reads it back). Works in plain debug *and* release builds. **If you implemented or modified ANY user-visible UI (panel, dock, strip, modal, theme, widget), screenshot before claiming the work is done — unit tests verify code correctness, not pixels.** The Read tool can open the returned PNG directly, so you can see what you painted without round-tripping through the user. **Canonical launch path for screenshots: `script/run-mcp --debug --headless`** (the native HeadlessClient + WgpuHeadlessRenderer route from ADR-0002; no Xvfb, no X server). After opening a session, drive the UI before snapping: `windows.focus` → `windows.dispatch_action {action_name: "console_panel::ToggleFocus"}` (or the analogous panel action) → `workspace.screenshot {solution_id: "...", format: "png"}`. Sample call shape: `solution_id` (not `window_id`) is the screenshot param; the returned PNG arrives inside the MCP `content` array as an `{"type":"image","data":"<base64>"}` block (NOT in `structuredContent`). **Do NOT try `xvfb-run … --display` as a fallback:** NVIDIA's Vulkan ICD silently fails the offscreen pass under Xvfb (no DRI3 → adapter selection picks NVIDIA discrete → render-attachment never rasterises), producing a uniform dark-slate PNG every time — see `docs/findings/2026-05-headless-screenshot-blank.md` for the full story and ADR-0002 for why native headless is the answer. macOS non-test builds also fall back to the blank error (the Metal `render_to_image` override is still `cfg`-gated; ungate it if a macOS agent ever drives this). `import -window root /tmp/screen.png` (ImageMagick) / `grim` (Wayland) still work for grabbing a real X display when you need to see window stacking, but for "what is the editor painting" prefer `workspace.screenshot` over the native headless build.

**Architecture:** `editor_mcp` crate owns lifecycle (`SingleInstanceLock`, server bind, broadcast). Tools are registered from each domain crate's `init` (`solutions::init`, `workspace::init`) via `editor_mcp::register_tool`. Event-source coordinator is in `solutions::event_sources` (kept out of `editor_mcp` to avoid a `editor_mcp → solutions/workspace/project` dep cycle that earlier phases had to resolve).

# Rust coding guidelines

* Prioritize code correctness and clarity. Speed and efficiency are secondary priorities unless otherwise specified.
* Do not write organizational or comments that summarize the code. Comments should only be written in order to explain "why" the code is written in some way in the case there is a reason that is tricky / non-obvious.
* Prefer implementing functionality in existing files unless it is a new logical component. Avoid creating many small files.
* Avoid using functions that panic like `unwrap()`, instead use mechanisms like `?` to propagate errors.
* Be careful with operations like indexing which may panic if the indexes are out of bounds.
* Never silently discard errors with `let _ =` on fallible operations. Always handle errors appropriately:
  - Propagate errors with `?` when the calling function should handle them
  - Use `.log_err()` or similar when you need to ignore errors but want visibility
  - Use explicit error handling with `match` or `if let Err(...)` when you need custom logic
  - Example: avoid `let _ = client.request(...).await?;` - use `client.request(...).await?;` instead
* When implementing async operations that may fail, ensure errors propagate to the UI layer so users get meaningful feedback.
* Never create files with `mod.rs` paths - prefer `src/some_module.rs` instead of `src/some_module/mod.rs`.
* When creating new crates, prefer specifying the library root path in `Cargo.toml` using `[lib] path = "...rs"` instead of the default `lib.rs`, to maintain consistent and descriptive naming (e.g., `gpui.rs` or `main.rs`).
* Avoid creative additions unless explicitly requested
* Use full words for variable names (no abbreviations like "q" for "queue")
* Use variable shadowing to scope clones in async contexts for clarity, minimizing the lifetime of borrowed references.
  Example:
  ```rust
  executor.spawn({
      let task_ran = task_ran.clone();
      async move {
          *task_ran.borrow_mut() = true;
      }
  });
  ```

# Timers in tests

* In GPUI tests, prefer GPUI executor timers over `smol::Timer::after(...)` when you need timeouts, delays, or to drive `run_until_parked()`:
  - Use `cx.background_executor().timer(duration).await` (or `cx.background_executor.timer(duration).await` in `TestAppContext`) so the work is scheduled on GPUI's dispatcher.
  - Avoid `smol::Timer::after(...)` for test timeouts when you rely on `run_until_parked()`, because it may not be tracked by GPUI's scheduler and can lead to "nothing left to run" when pumping.

# GPUI

GPUI is a UI framework which also provides primitives for state and concurrency management.

## Context

Context types allow interaction with global state, windows, entities, and system services. They are typically passed to functions as the argument named `cx`. When a function takes callbacks they come after the `cx` parameter.

* `App` is the root context type, providing access to global state and read and update of entities.
* `Context<T>` is provided when updating an `Entity<T>`. This context dereferences into `App`, so functions which take `&App` can also take `&Context<T>`.
* `AsyncApp` and `AsyncWindowContext` are provided by `cx.spawn` and `cx.spawn_in`. These can be held across await points.

## `Window`

`Window` provides access to the state of an application window. It is passed to functions as an argument named `window` and comes before `cx` when present. It is used for managing focus, dispatching actions, directly drawing, getting user input state, etc.

## Entities

An `Entity<T>` is a handle to state of type `T`. With `thing: Entity<T>`:

* `thing.entity_id()` returns `EntityId`
* `thing.downgrade()` returns `WeakEntity<T>`
* `thing.read(cx: &App)` returns `&T`.
* `thing.read_with(cx, |thing: &T, cx: &App| ...)` returns the closure's return value.
* `thing.update(cx, |thing: &mut T, cx: &mut Context<T>| ...)` allows the closure to mutate the state, and provides a `Context<T>` for interacting with the entity. It returns the closure's return value.
* `thing.update_in(cx, |thing: &mut T, window: &mut Window, cx: &mut Context<T>| ...)` takes a `AsyncWindowContext` or `VisualTestContext`. It's the same as `update` while also providing the `Window`.

Within the closures, the inner `cx` provided to the closure must be used instead of the outer `cx` to avoid issues with multiple borrows.

Trying to update an entity while it's already being updated must be avoided as this will cause a panic.

`WeakEntity<T>` is a weak handle. It has `read_with`, `update`, and `update_in` methods that work the same, but always return an `anyhow::Result` so that they can fail if the entity no longer exists. This can be useful to avoid memory leaks - if entities have mutually recursive handles to each other they will never be dropped.

## Concurrency

All use of entities and UI rendering occurs on a single foreground thread.

`cx.spawn(async move |cx| ...)` runs an async closure on the foreground thread. Within the closure, `cx` is `&mut AsyncApp`.

When the outer cx is a `Context<T>`, the use of `spawn` instead looks like `cx.spawn(async move |this, cx| ...)`, where `this: WeakEntity<T>` and `cx: &mut AsyncApp`.

To do work on other threads, `cx.background_spawn(async move { ... })` is used. Often this background task is awaited on by a foreground task which uses the results to update state.

Both `cx.spawn` and `cx.background_spawn` return a `Task<R>`, which is a future that can be awaited upon. If this task is dropped, then its work is cancelled. To prevent this one of the following must be done:

* Awaiting the task in some other async context.
* Detaching the task via `task.detach()` or `task.detach_and_log_err(cx)`, allowing it to run indefinitely.
* Storing the task in a field, if the work should be halted when the struct is dropped.

A task which doesn't do anything but provide a value can be created with `Task::ready(value)`.

## Elements

The `Render` trait is used to render some state into an element tree that is laid out using flexbox layout. An `Entity<T>` where `T` implements `Render` is sometimes called a "view".

Example:

```
struct TextWithBorder(SharedString);

impl Render for TextWithBorder {
    fn render(&mut self, _window: &mut Window, _cx: &mut Context<Self>) -> impl IntoElement {
        div().border_1().child(self.0.clone())
    }
}
```

Since `impl IntoElement for SharedString` exists, it can be used as an argument to `child`. `SharedString` is used to avoid copying strings, and is either an `&'static str` or `Arc<str>`.

UI components that are constructed just to be turned into elements can instead implement the `RenderOnce` trait, which is similar to `Render`, but its `render` method takes ownership of `self` and receives `&mut App` instead of `&mut Context<Self>`. Types that implement this trait can use `#[derive(IntoElement)]` to use them directly as children.

The style methods on elements are similar to those used by Tailwind CSS.

If some attributes or children of an element tree are conditional, `.when(condition, |this| ...)` can be used to run the closure only when `condition` is true. Similarly, `.when_some(option, |this, value| ...)` runs the closure when the `Option` has a value.

## Input events

Input event handlers can be registered on an element via methods like `.on_click(|event, window, cx: &mut App| ...)`.

Often event handlers will want to update the entity that's in the current `Context<T>`. The `cx.listener` method provides this - its use looks like `.on_click(cx.listener(|this: &mut T, event, window, cx: &mut Context<T>| ...)`.

## Actions

Actions are dispatched via user keyboard interaction or in code via `window.dispatch_action(SomeAction.boxed_clone(), cx)` or `focus_handle.dispatch_action(&SomeAction, window, cx)`.

Actions with no data defined with the `actions!(some_namespace, [SomeAction, AnotherAction])` macro call. Otherwise the `Action` derive macro is used. Doc comments on actions are displayed to the user.

Action handlers can be registered on an element via the event handler `.on_action(|action, window, cx| ...)`. Like other event handlers, this is often used with `cx.listener`.

## Notify

When a view's state has changed in a way that may affect its rendering, it should call `cx.notify()`. This will cause the view to be rerendered. It will also cause any observe callbacks registered for the entity with `cx.observe` to be called.

## Entity events

While updating an entity (`cx: Context<T>`), it can emit an event using `cx.emit(event)`. Entities register which events they can emit by declaring `impl EventEmitter<EventType> for EntityType {}`.

Other entities can then register a callback to handle these events by doing `cx.subscribe(other_entity, |this, other_entity, event, cx| ...)`. This will return a `Subscription` which deregisters the callback when dropped.  Typically `cx.subscribe` happens when creating a new entity and the subscriptions are stored in a `_subscriptions: Vec<Subscription>` field.

## Build guidelines

- Use `./script/clippy` instead of `cargo clippy`

# Pull request hygiene

When an agent opens or updates a pull request, it must:

- Use a clear, correctly capitalized, imperative PR title (for example, `Fix crash in project panel`).
- Avoid conventional commit prefixes in PR titles (`fix:`, `feat:`, `docs:`, etc.).
- Avoid trailing punctuation in PR titles.
- Optionally prefix the title with a crate name when one crate is the clear scope (for example, `git_ui: Add history view`).
- Include a `Release Notes:` section as the final section in the PR body.
- Use one bullet under `Release Notes:`:
  - `- Added ...`, `- Fixed ...`, or `- Improved ...` for user-facing changes, or
  - `- N/A` for docs-only and other non-user-facing changes.
- Format release notes exactly with a blank line after the heading, for example:

```
Release Notes:

- N/A
```

# Crash Investigation

## Sentry Integration
- Crash investigation prompts: `.factory/prompts/crash/investigate.md`
- Crash fix prompts: `.factory/prompts/crash/fix.md`
- Fetch crash reports: `script/sentry-fetch <issue-id>`
- Generate investigation prompt from crash: `script/crash-to-prompt <issue-id>`

# Documenting fork-local work

**Every fork-local addition or architectural decision on top of upstream MUST be recorded in `FORK.md`** at the repo root. That file is the single index for "what's different here" and the *why* behind non-obvious choices. Update it when:

- A new fork-local crate is added (one row in the crates table + a one-line purpose).
- An upstream file gets its **first** local modification (one row in the touched-files table). The point of the table is no longer "merge cost" but: "list of files where a future cherry-pick from upstream won't apply cleanly — reconcile by hand." Subsequent edits to an already-listed file don't need a new row.
- A non-obvious architectural decision is made — record it as a numbered entry under "Key architectural decisions" with **why** (the constraint that ruled out the obvious approach) and **how to apply** (concrete guidance for future sessions).
- A locked rebrand identifier changes (cross-reference the spec; keep `.rules` § "Locked rebrand identifiers" in sync).

Don't put per-crate module layouts, type catalogs, or status updates in `FORK.md` — those go stale fast. Use `git log` for status, code for layout, and per-crate `.rules` for traps to avoid.

# Rules Hygiene

These `.rules` files are read by every agent session. Keep them high-signal.

## After any agentic session
If you discover a non-obvious pattern that would help future sessions, include a **"Suggested .rules additions"** heading in your PR description with the proposed text. Do **not** edit `.rules` inline during normal feature/fix work. Reviewers decide what gets merged.

Mechanical post-feature maintenance is fine without a separate suggestion (e.g. bumping the tool catalog count when a new MCP namespace lands). Architectural rules and "trap to avoid" entries follow the suggestion path.

## High bar for new rules
Editing or clarifying existing rules is always welcome. New rules must meet **all three** criteria:
1. **Non-obvious** — someone familiar with the codebase would still get it wrong without the rule.
2. **Repeatedly encountered** — it came up more than once (multiple hits in one session counts).
3. **Specific enough to act on** — a concrete instruction, not a vague principle.

Rules that apply to a single crate belong in that crate's own `.rules` file, not the repo root.

## What NOT to put in `.rules`
Avoid architectural descriptions of a crate (module layout, data flow, key types). These go stale fast and the agent can gather them by reading the code. Rules should be **traps to avoid**, not **maps to follow**.

## No drive-by additions
Rules emerge from validated patterns, not one-off observations. The workflow is:
1. Agent notes a pattern during a session.
2. Team validates the pattern in code review.
3. A dedicated commit adds the rule with context on *why* it exists.
